		<td>
			<h1 align="center">Motivation of Query-by-Example Systems</h1>
			<hr>			
			
			<p><b>Initial intention (from DBMS):</b></p>
			<ul>
				<li>Shields user from learning complicated query language (easier to use compared to SQL or other query language)</li>
				<li>Achieve independence (Changes in underlying implementation does not influence users, not unique in QBE)</li>
			</ul>
			
			<p><b>Additional motivation (from Multimedia):</b></p>
			<ul>
				<li>Increase expressiveness of the multimedia query that text alone cannot describe.</li>
				<li><b>Analogy</b>:<br>MasterCard - <i>&quot;There’s something money can’t buy.&nbsp; For everything else, there’s MasterCard</i>.&quot;<br>
				QBE - <i>&quot;There’s something in pictures that word can’t describe.  For everything else, there’s text-based search engine.&quot;</i></li>
			</ul>
			
			<p><b>Issues with tags and annotation:</b></p>
			<ul>
				<li>Cost - Tagging and annotation is expensive because it 
				requires human to interpret the semantics to each multimedia 
				objects (images, video, audio).</li>
				<li>Coverage - Description of the multimedia objects are 
				typically incomplete.<br>
				<img border="0" src="images/cousin.JPG" width="287" height="216"><br>
				(baby, toy, camera, ear, table, etc.)</li>
				<li>Inconsistency - Humans are inconsistent.&nbsp; Tagging the 
				same picture may not give you the same set of tags every time 
				you ask them. (not always a bad thing though)<br>
				<img border="0" src="images/cousin.JPG" width="287" height="216"><br>
				(chair, hair, infants, dinosaur, etc.)</li>
			</ul>
			<p><b>Because of the above issues, people use computers (such as a 
			QBE system) to extract features from multimedia objects.&nbsp; In 
			general, these system does fairly good job when the size of search 
			space is large.</b></td>
	</tr>
</table>
</center>

